{
  "text": "It is not known which mechanism was utilized by the last common ancestor of nidovirids and, thus, which represents divergence from the original model. It has been suggested that convergent evolution has resulted in the mechanism for discontinuous negative-strand synthesis arising multiple times within the Nidovirales [CITATION_1] . Similarly, whether the initial role of the TRS motif was to merely stimulate the attenuation of RNA synthesis or to direct template switching is not known. Our data suggest that transcription mechanisms in the Nidovirales fall into multiple categories, each requiring a distinct role of the TRS: (i) homology-driven reinitiation (canonical discontinuous RNA synthesis, as seen in coronaviruses and arteriviruses and, to a low extent, EToV N protein-coding mRNAs), (ii) structure-driven discontinuous transcription (EToV S gene), and (iii) transcription termination (EToV M, HE, and the majority of N protein-coding transcripts). These mechanisms require an RdRp which is prone to template switching when even relatively short homologous sequences are present, potentially leading to a large number of irrelevant transcripts being produced (as previously observed in an arterivirus [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ) and also facilitating the production of defective interfering RNAs [CITATION_4] and recombinant strains [CITATION_5] .",
  "correct_citation": {
